Snobbery. Most people don't like it or enjoy it, and we at Hook certainly keep a point to stray away from it.

Very few people would proudly identify as a snob.

So why do so many people call themselves "coffee snobs"?

Firstly, the term snobbery can mean different things to different people. For the sake of the blog post, we're going to define and explain what we mean when we speak of the snob factor.

Snobbery is when someone thinks they are better than you AND they are a jerk about it. Snobbery is uninviting, unhospitable, and elitist. Snobbery is a lack of empathy. Humans are all worth the same regardless of education, background, culture, or personality...and snobbery doesn't uphold those values.

Yeah, snobbery isn't good.

When individuals identify as coffee snobs, they usually mean that they enjoy good coffee and refuse to partake in a beverage of low standards. Those aren't real coffee snobs. Those are just people who like good coffee.

[These coffee connoisseurs simply enjoy their coffee, and they enjoy intentionally grown coffee. If someone they know doesn't care for quality coffee, it doesn't matter. Life goes on.]

The REAL coffee snobs look down on those who drink something other than artisan crafted coffee. True coffee snobs like these are notorious for yelling at children and not truly appreciating the coffee community.

[Coffee snobs are selfish. Coffee is about them. Not the farmers and the roasters who make coffee happen.]

If you've ever accidentally identified as a coffee snob, don't worry! It's completely fine. We aren't your mother, berating you for doing something bad. Coffee snobbery is such a loosely defined term, and it can be difficult to differentiate the good and bad.

&nbsp;

<h2><strong>Deterring the Snob</strong></h2>

If you enjoy craft coffee, it can be difficult to not come off as a snob. It sounds weird, but it's true. Many-a-coffee-snob roam the streets. When people see you grinding your own beans or brewing with an aeropress, they may assume that you are one of the snobs. Even if you invite someone into your home and offer to brew them a cup of coffee, they may still perceive you as the bad guy. It's not fair, but that's the way of things.

So as advocates of the specialty coffee craft, how do we stray away from snobbery? How do we show others that coffee brings individuals together?

Here's a strategy guide we developed; it should be quite handy:

<strong><em>Educate</em></strong> - This is huge. If someone calls you a snob for enjoying your specialty coffee, kindly ask them why they think so. Proceed to educate them on some simple coffee processes, and invite them to brew a cup with you!

Education is the bridge between ignorance and understanding. If you explain why you grind your beans fresh, why coffee farmers should be paid fairly, you may just make an impression - a good one.

<strong><em>Be Nice </em></strong>- Never respond in anger to an immature comment concerning your habits or preferences. Hear people out when they make fun of your "coffee snobbery," and proceed to educate. If they don't listen, smile at them and loudly grind some coffee beans. Foolproof.

<strong><em>Share </em></strong>- Sharing is caring! If someone questions your coffee habits/addiction, share with them. Show them the glory that is coffee! Maybe you'll convert a few skeptics while you're at it.

<strong>Run Away </strong>- If none of the options above do any good, throw some coffee beans to discombobulate the enemy, and run away. Laugh villainously too. You're sure to make an impression.

All jokes aside, educating others is important. Hook delves into the science of coffee to not only offer a tasty beverage; we aim to teach the world more about sustainability. Coffee can be explored, enjoyed, and cherished.

There's no room for snobbery in the world of coffee.

&nbsp;

Happy Brewing, Friends!

The Hook Coffee Team

